              <span id="reviewTextContainer4089806659" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18149177323570370705">I feel like I don&apos;t have any thoughts on this even though it&apos;s a book that I should have a lot of thoughts on. What I expected was teachings directly from the Dalai Lama and maybe some information on his past, basically a mix of biography and self-help. The actual author of the book is Howard Cutler, listed as co-author, and we get more information from him than we do the Dalai Lama, who contributed to the book only in the form of conversations with Cutler.<br/><br/>Cutler annoyed me a little bit and I fo</span>
  <span id="freeText18149177323570370705" style="display:none">I feel like I don't have any thoughts on this even though it's a book that I should have a lot of thoughts on. What I expected was teachings directly from the Dalai Lama and maybe some information on his past, basically a mix of biography and self-help. The actual author of the book is Howard Cutler, listed as co-author, and we get more information from him than we do the Dalai Lama, who contributed to the book only in the form of conversations with Cutler.<br /><br />Cutler annoyed me a little bit and I found the way he questioned the teachings in order to expand them to be kind of naïve and unnecessary at times. On top of that, a lot of what was discussed was actually already how I try to see the world so I didn't learn anything profoundly new or mind-expanding. It was interesting in some parts and I'm glad I listened to it on audiobook, but I won't return to this and honestly don't really recommend it.</span>
