<div id="review_3503066479" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3503066479" />
    <a title="Chris Dietzel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19351209-chris-dietzel"><img alt="Chris Dietzel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1501356106p2/19351209.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3503066479?book_show_action=true">Aug 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chris Dietzel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chris Dietzel" href="/user/show/19351209-chris-dietzel">Chris Dietzel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3503066479" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4889298942603744262">I enjoyed the Dalai Lama&apos;s take on what it means to be happy and how that state can be achieved. My favorite idea of his from this book was that if there are five billion people in the world, there should be five billion different religions, and people need to be skeptical of the world and what they are told rather than just blindly accept others&apos; religions or views. <br/><br/>I could have done without the psychiatrist trying to interpret the Dalai Lama&apos;s teaching but that didn&apos;t detract too much for me. </span>
  <span id="freeText4889298942603744262" style="display:none">I enjoyed the Dalai Lama's take on what it means to be happy and how that state can be achieved. My favorite idea of his from this book was that if there are five billion people in the world, there should be five billion different religions, and people need to be skeptical of the world and what they are told rather than just blindly accept others' religions or views. <br /><br />I could have done without the psychiatrist trying to interpret the Dalai Lama's teaching but that didn't detract too much for me. In terms of a book that presents easily accessible Buddhist philosophy, I would more heavily recommend <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7579.Awakening_the_Buddha_Within_Eight_Steps_to_Enlightenment" title="Awakening the Buddha Within Eight Steps to Enlightenment by Surya Das" rel="nofollow noopener">Awakening the Buddha Within: Eight Steps to Enlightenment</a> but this one is nice too because it's coming largely from the Dalai Lama himself.</span>
